    <h2>Key Things to Check Before Buying a Commercial Refrigerator in India</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Energy Star Rating</strong>: In India's hot climate, refrigerators run constantly. A 5-star energy-rated unit can save ₹10,000–₹30,000 per year in electricity versus a 2-star unit</li>
      <li><strong>Temperature Range</strong>: Verify it can maintain 2–8°C in your ambient kitchen temperature (Indian kitchens can reach 35–40°C in summer)</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor type</strong>: Hermetic compressors (most common) are reliable; variable speed compressors save energy</li>
      <li><strong>Shelf configuration</strong>: Check that shelves are removable and adjustable for your storage needs</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket quality</strong>: Worn gaskets are the most common cause of temperature failure. Check them carefully on used units</li>
      <li><strong>Service network</strong>: AMC (Annual Maintenance Contract) availability in your city</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial refrigerator in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial refrigerator prices in India range from ₹25,000 for a basic single-door reach-in model to ₹2,00,000 for a triple-door stainless steel refrigerator. Blast chillers cost ₹1,20,000 – ₹9,00,000. Walk-in cold rooms range from ₹2,50,000 to ₹20 lakh or more depending on size. Display refrigerators for bakeries cost ₹35,000 – ₹2,50,000.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the difference between a commercial and domestic refrigerator? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial refrigerators are built for continuous operation (24/7), can maintain precise temperatures in hot ambient conditions (like Indian kitchens at 40°C), are made from stainless steel (food-safe and cleanable), have more powerful compressors, and meet food safety standards. Domestic refrigerators are not designed for commercial kitchen conditions and will fail prematurely, void warranties, and may not maintain safe food temperatures in hot commercial kitchen environments.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which commercial refrigerator brand is best in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For Indian-made equipment: Blue Star and Voltas offer the best combination of quality, price, and service network. For imported equipment: Hoshizaki and Williams are premium choices used in luxury hotels. For bakery display cases: imported brands from Italy (Criocabin, Arneg) or local fabricators offer good options. The best brand depends on your budget and specific requirements — contact us for personalised recommendations.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much electricity does a commercial refrigerator use in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A commercial double-door reach-in refrigerator typically uses 3–8 units (kWh) of electricity per day, depending on size, energy rating, ambient temperature, and how often doors are opened. At ₹8 per unit (commercial rate), that's ₹24–₹64 per day, or ₹720–₹1,920 per month. A 5-star rated unit uses about 30–40% less electricity than a 2-star unit — significant savings over a 10-year life.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq_q">Is a blast chiller necessary for an Indian bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A blast chiller is essential if you're operating a bake-off bakery, complying with HACCP standards, or producing high-volume chilled pastries. For smaller bakeries making fresh products for same-day sale, a blast chiller is less critical. However, FSSAI's food safety guidelines are becoming stricter and blast chillers may become a compliance requirement for larger operations. If you're planning for growth, it's worth including one in your setup.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

